<HEAD>PARNASSUS.</HEAD>
<LG>
<L>PARNASSUS hight, there is&mdash;nor tell I tales&mdash;</L>
<L>A mountain, high as any in North Wales:</L>
<L>Where &s;tanding, in climes foreign o$ our own,</L>
<L>Is known to Poets, and to them alone;</L>
<L>Nor will be other, while old Time &s;hall pace on,</L>
<L>For ev'r$ Poet is a &s;worn Free-m$&s;on.</L>
<L>On this high mountain the Nine Mu&s;es dwell,</L>
<L>Twin &s;i&s;ters all, as go&s;&s;ip Fame can tell.</L>
<L>Here are, be&s;ides ten thou&s;and pretty things,</L>
<L>A magick Fountain, and a $Word$ with Wings.</L>
<L>Whene'er the waters of this &s;tream are quaff'd,</L>
<L>Knowledge is giv'n, proportion'd to the draught;</L>
<L>Who mounts this Hor&s;e, o'er all the world may fly,</L>
<L>Soar to the &s;tars, and all pur&s;uit $Word$.</L>
<L>This mountain's top, in bre$dth &s;$me dozen miles,</L>
<L>Pre&s;ents a &s;cene, where Nature ever &s;miles.</L>
<L>There barebon'd Winter never yet was &s;een;</L>
<L>The lawns and meadows wear un$$ding gr$en:</L>
<L>Spring's milder &s;un there always &s;heds his beams;</L>
<L>$Word$ their v$$du$e, chry&s;tal are then &s;treams.</L>
<L><PB N="10" REF="10">
Silks, &s;atins, velvets, mu&s;lins, and &s;o forth,</L>
<L>Compo&s;e the flow'rs: the f$$$ts boa&s;t greater worth;</L>
<L>Jewels are they, mo&s;t exqui&s;ite and rare,</L>
<L>And $vo$y boughs the precious burdens bear.</L>
<L>There birds of &s;ilver, and refulgent gold,</L>
<L>Enamell'd o'er, mo&s;t beauteous to behold,</L>
<L>Sing on a model novel quite, nor plann'd ill,</L>
<L>As A$ne's fine airs, or choru&s;&s;es from Handel!</L>
<L>Divine&s;t odou$s the rapt &s;en&s;es greet,</L>
<L>Spice-crown'd Arabia breathes not half &s;o &s;weet:</L>
<L>None here want food, &s;o Lent eternal keep;</L>
<L>Night comes not here, and no one wants to &s;leep.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>Thence P$ets &s;pring; and thence tho&s;e &s;cenes they draw,</L>
<L>Tho&s;e <HI>ti&s;&s;ue</HI> &s;cenes, which no man ever &s;aw:</L>
<L>Where $$$ia &s;leeps upon the <HI>downy</HI> gra&s;s;</L>
<L>And makes the <HI>&s;ilv'ry</HI> &s;tream her dre&s;&s;ing gla&s;s;</L>
<L>Where <HI>amorous</HI> &s;unbeams paint her with the ro&s;e,</L>
<L>And <HI>love &s;ick</HI> Zephyrs fan her to repo&s;e!</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>Thence Poets &s;pring; no wonder, then, their knowledge</L>
<L>Exceeds the my&s;teries of either college;</L>
<L>No wonder, then, the Poet, in his flight,</L>
<L>So often &s;oars beyond all mortal &s;ight.</L>
<L>Thence are the flow'rs that form his boa&s;ted wreath;</L>
<L>Tho&s;e <HI>Lawn$</HI> flow'rs, that wither with a breath;</L>
<L>Thence the rare fruits, with which his way is &s;trew'd,</L>
<L>Plea&s;ant for light, but worthle&s;s all for food!</L>
<L>And thence, though Poets &s;ing &s;uch &s;trains divine,</L>
<L>Rarely their $$$a$s procure them means to dine.</L>
<L>Ah! rarely Poets may refre&s;hment take,</L>
<L>And &s;leep will &s;till the hungry &s;oul for&s;ake.</L>
<L>Ye ardent vouths, who hourly &s;igh for fame,</L>
<L>Ah! covet not the Bard's too envied name:</L>
<L>Few are his $ovs, unnumber'd are his woes;</L>
<L>And the&s;e &s;ub&s;tan$ial, but ideal tho&s;e.</L>
<L>His plea&s;ures few, and they but gay deceits;</L>
<L>He &s;tarves, poor devill amid fancied &s;weets.</L>
</LG>
